<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-245-016  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 245 016.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  March 13 1990 n1383* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>French insurers reveal the costs of computer breakdowns, sabotage.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Agence France-Presse (reports).andO;Topic:     Computer CrimesInsuranceFranceSabotageComputer VirusesFraudReports.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FRENCH INSURERS REVEAL THE COSTS OF COMPUTERandM;BREAKDOWNS, SABOTAGEandM;Computer crime cost the French over $700m dollars in 1989, an increase of10.2% on 1988, with computer fraud, sabotage and software corruptionresponsible for a large part of this figure, reports Agence France Presse.andO;The statistics were released at the Paris Securicom conference on computersecurity by APSAD, the collective body of French insurance companies, whosereport showed that this accounted for around a half of the total losses dueto the misuse or abuse of information technology.andP;  Computer breakdowns, ofwhich there were 11,900 cases, cost $400,000, while computer errors accountedfor losses of $300,000.andP;  The 10% increase puts the number of computer crimesrecorded up to 1,800; what's more, some of the saboteurs have banded togetherto form an organisation called Clodo slang for tramp which like the Ludditemachinebreakers in the North of England at the start of the 19th century, arededicated to undermining the infiltration of technology into the workplace.andO;</TEXT></DOC>